    <h3 class="title"><a href="/battlestar/moore-speaks-bsg-backstory-and-fracks-it#comment-6725" class="active">Cycle of Time</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://www.lisapaitzspindler.com/blog" rel="nofollow">Lisa</a> (not verified) on Tue, 2009-01-20 08:20.</div>
    <div class="content"><p><em>I am perfectly fine with a writer wanting to show us a concept of history repeating it self, and moving in cycles. Characters and whole societies trapped in a cycle of self-destruction. That’s all good. But in reality, the things that repeat in those cycles are patterns of history, not people writing the same song with twisted lyrics, word for word, note for note. It just doesn’t work that way.</em></p>
<p>The Cycles of Time are connected. I prefer they be connected by some kind of technological development rather than mystical. If humans/Cylons have been resurrecting for eons it would be logical for some of each Cycle's knowledge be saved somehow. I just keep thinking about Ellen's words to Tigh at the end of "Sometimes a Great Notion" that "all is in place." If they knew the end of the world was coming and created some kind of resurrection hub, you can bet they also would have stored at least some of their civilization's knowledge. Shakespeare and Dylan would certainly have been included. Maybe there have been so many cycles that the information is corrupted or the media of storage is organic and therefore accessing it is not just as simple as finding a file on your hard drive.</p>
